ce:section.ce:para:
When strong acids such as H2SO4 and HCl were used as solvents in a graphitization process, the PL emission of the resulting NCQDs were red-shifted with a broad PL emission linewidth (∼100 nm FWHM). Strong acids induced the oxidation of NCQDs and increased in the density of oxygen-included functional groups on the surfaces, which acted as trap sites for charge carriers, resulting in the red-shifted PL emission and broad FWHM [20,21,47,48]. In the literature, a narrow FWHM with ∼35 nm achieved by edge amination which was replaced the oxygen-included functional groups with amine groups due to the fact that the oxygen-included functional groups leads to the fluctuation of electrons in LUMO level, resulting in broad FWHM [28]. In our study, when a diluted H2SO4 was employed, the resulting NCQDs showed the blue-shifted PL emission with a narrow FWHM (∼45 nm). When the concentration of H2SO4 was increased, the PL emission was also red-shifted from 377 nm (1 M H2SO4) to 450 nm (3 M H2SO4). This phenomenon corresponded to red-shifted PL emission of NCQDs when a concentrated strong acid was used in the graphitization [48]. In addition, when a diluted HCl was used as a solvent, the PL emissions were red-shifted to 475 nm and 630 nm and the FWHM was narrowed to ∼62 nm due to the increase in the amount of doped nitrogen on the NCQDs (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). This corresponded to a red-shifted PL emission with increasing the density of the doped nitrogen [47]. Therefore, we assumed that a diluted H2SO4 induces the blue-shifted PL emission and a diluted HCl accelerates the nitrogen doping on the NCQDs, resulting in red-shifted PL emission.
